{
  "card_id": "seek_and_destroy_profile",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Seek and Destroy Profile",
  "aliases": [
    "consolidation day profile",
    "Consolidation Day Profile",
    "consolidation profile",
    "indecision candle profile",
    "Indecision Candle Profile",
    "indecision profile",
    "seek and destroy",
    "Seek and Destroy",
    "seek and destroy pattern",
    "Seek and Destroy Pattern"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A daily indecision candle where open and close are near the same level. London sweeps both Asia high and low without displacement, creating a range. New York oscillates between range extremes, often forming a broadening formation. Typically occurs before high-impact news or on quiet days.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "The daily candle closes at approximately the same price it opened, forming a doji or near-doji structure with no meaningful net directional move.",
    "During London session, both the Asia high and Asia low are swept, but without a closing displacement beyond either level.",
    "Each time price exits the established range (Asia or London range), it fails to displace and returns back inside the range.",
    "Alternatively, if London has already created most of the daily range before New York opens, New York is expected to consolidate rather than expand, qualifying as a Seek and Destroy condition.",
    "In New York session, price reacts at London high and low as points of interest for reversals or targets.",
    "A broadening formation (outside bar) emerges on higher timeframes.",
    "The profile is more probable following a very large range day or on sessions preceding high-impact news events (CPI, FOMC, NFP).",
    "On a lower time frame, price action appears as whipsaw oscillation between the range extremes rather than a clean directional expansion.",
    "The pattern has fractal properties; the same Seek and Destroy sub-pattern can be observed on lower timeframes.",
    "Mark the range's buyside and sellside liquidity as true boundaries; observe if price deviates from the range and returns inside."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Preferably avoid trading this profile as it lacks expansion. If trading, reverse breakout strategies: trade from outside the range back into it. Use London range's equilibrium (50% midpoint) as primary target, then the opposing range extreme. London extremes act as points of interest. Asia range and daily open serve as magnet targets. May combine with Power of Three and SMT for entry confirmation. Do not attempt breakout or expansion trades.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Attempting to trade directional breakouts or expansions out of the range, expecting price to sustain a move beyond the range extremes.",
    "Treating the profile as a standard London Reversal or NY Manipulation setup and entering for a large directional move.",
    "Ignoring the profile entirely without recognizing it as a signal to stay out of the market, leading to unnecessary losses on whipsaw price action.",
    "Failing to recognize that the pattern often occurs before high-impact news events (CPI, FOMC, NFP).",
    "Expecting New York to deliver a large directional move when London has already exhausted most of the daily range.",
    "Entering before New York confirms reaction at London points of interest.",
    "Ignoring higher timeframe context, such as the formation of an outside bar (broadening formation).",
    "Not marking the range's equilibrium and premium/discount zones, leading to incorrect target setting.",
    "Entering before price fully returns inside the range, getting caught by inducement."
  ],
